  "text": "HTTP connection manager route matching in Envoy is implemented across several C++ source files in the envoyproxy/envoy repository (version v1.31.2). The implementation is split into three main components:\n\n## Virtual Host Selection\nThe `RouteMatcher` class in `source/common/router/config_impl.h` and `config_impl.cc` handles virtual host selection. It provides:\n- `findVirtualHost()` method: Performs host/domain matching against request headers to select the appropriate virtual host. Handles exact matches, suffix wildcards, and prefix wildcards.\n- `findWildcardVirtualHost()` method: Implements wildcard matching algorithm for virtual hosts, supporting longest wildcard match patterns (e.g., \"*-bar.baz.com\" matches before \"*.baz.com\").\n- The RouteMatcher maintains data structures: `virtual_hosts_` (hash map for exact matches), `wildcard_virtual_host_suffixes_` and `wildcard_virtual_host_prefixes_` (maps for wildcard patterns sorted by specificity).\n\n## Route Matching Algorithm\nThe route matching logic is implemented in `CommonVirtualHostImpl` and `VirtualHostImpl` classes in `source/common/router/config_impl.h` and `config_impl.cc`. Key components include:\n- `VirtualHostImpl::getRouteFromEntries()`: Iterates through configured routes and calls `matches()` on each route entry to find the first matching route.\n- `VirtualHostImpl::getRouteFromRoutes()`: Similar pattern for route lists, processes routes in order.\n- Multiple route entry implementation classes handle different path matching patterns:\n  - `PrefixRouteEntryImpl`: Matches request paths by prefix\n  - `PathRouteEntryImpl`: Matches exact request paths\n  - `RegexRouteEntryImpl`: Matches paths using regular expressions\n  - `UriTemplateMatcherRouteEntryImpl`: Matches paths using URI template patterns\n  - `ConnectRouteEntryImpl`: Matches CONNECT requests\n  - `PathSeparatedPrefixRouteEntryImpl`: Matches path-separated prefix patterns\n- Each route entry class implements `matches()` method from the `Matchable` interface to evaluate request headers against the route's match criteria.\n- Route matching also considers additional criteria: header matching, query parameters, runtime features, TLS context, and gRPC options.\n\n## Route Action Dispatch\nThe router filter in `source/common/router/router.h` and `router.cc` orchestrates the routing decision:\n- `Filter::decodeHeaders()` method (line 431 in router.cc): Main entry point that receives incoming request headers. It calls `callbacks_->route()` to trigger route matching.\n- The filter first checks for a matching route (line 454), handling the \"no route found\" case.\n- Then it checks for direct responses (line 466) which may generate local responses without contacting upstream clusters.\n- Finally, it extracts the route entry (line 492) and proceeds with the actual route action dispatch.\n- `RouteMatchAction` and `RouteListMatchAction` classes encapsulate actions to be taken when routes match in the matching tree.\n- The `FilterConfig` class provides configuration and factory context for the filter.\n\n## Configuration and Integration\nThe HTTP connection manager configuration is handled in `source/extensions/filters/network/http_connection_manager/config.h` and `config.cc`, which integrates the router configuration provider and route matching through the `RouteMatcher` instance managed by `CommonConfigImpl`.\n\nThe route matching flow chain: HTTP Request → RouteMatcher::findVirtualHost() (virtual host selection) → VirtualHostImpl::getRouteFromEntries() (route iteration) → RouteEntry::matches() (path/header matching) → Route Action Dispatch in Filter::decodeHeaders()."
}

